{{Expand French|topic=culture|date=April 2017}} [[File:Cinematheque quebecoise.JPG|thumb|The Cinémathèque québécoise.]] The '''Cinémathèque québécoise''' is a [[Film preservation|film conservatory]] in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada. Its purpose is to preserve and document film and television footage and related documents and artifacts for future use by the public.<ref name="Cinémathèque English">{{cite web|url=http://www.cinematheque.qc.ca/cinematheque/history.html|title=A STORY, A MISSION, A SPACE|work=Cinémathèque québécoise Web site|accessdate=2009-04-10}}</ref> The Cinémathèque's collections include over 35,000 films from all eras and countries, 25,000 television programmes, 28,000 posters, 600,000 photos, 2,000 pieces of historical equipment,<ref>[https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/montreal/film-found-colour-quebec-1.3505012 "Quebec home movie from 1929 may be some of earliest colour film"]. ''CBC News'', Julia Caron, Mar 28, 2016.</ref> 15,000 scripts and production documents, 45,000 books, 3,000 magazine titles, thousands of files as well as objects, props and costumes.<ref name="Cinémathèque English"/> The conservatory also includes a film theatre which screens rarely-seen film and video.<ref name="Bennett2018">{{cite book|author=Andrea Bennett|title=Moon Montréal|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JDo4DwAAQBAJ&pg=PT202|date=24 April 2018|publisher=Avalon Publishing|isbn=978-1-64049-315-5|page=202}}</ref>
It is located at 355 [[De Maisonneuve Boulevard]] East, in the city's [[Quartier Latin, Montreal|Quartier Latin]], which is also part of the new [[Quartier des Spectacles]] cultural district.<ref>[https://www.cnn.com/travel/article/montreal-most-interesting-neighborhoods/index.html "12 of Montreal's best neighborhoods"]. Joe Yogerst, ''CNN'' • 13 November 2017</ref> The [[Institut national de l'image et du son]] is located next door.<ref name="Barker">{{cite news|url=http://www.playbackonline.ca/articles/magazine/20021111/inis.html?print=yes|title=INIS grads breaking into biz|last=Rice-Barker|first=Leo|date=Nov 11, 2002|work=[[Playback (magazine)|Playback]]|publisher=Brunico Communications|accessdate=13 April 2010}}</ref>
==History== The Connaissance du cinéma, soon after renamed the Cinémathèque canadienne, was founded in 1963.<ref name="HabibMarie2013">{{cite book|author1=André Habib|author2=Michel Marie|title=L'avenir de la mémoire: Patrimoine, restauration et réemploi cinématographiques|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lHcQ9EXckkkC&pg=PA79|date=19 February 2013|publisher=Presses Univ. Septentrion|isbn=978-2-7574-0439-3|page=79}}</ref><ref>[https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/little-trace-remains-of-montreals-glamorous-theatre-era "Little trace remains of Montreal's glamorous theatre era"]. Linda Gyulai, ''Montreal Gazette'', May 13, 2015</ref>
In 1971 the institution was renamed Cinémathèque québécoise.<ref>{{Cite book|language = French|author1 = Yves Lever et Pierre Pageau|title = Chronologie du cinéma au Québec|location = Montréal (Québec), Canada|editor = Les 400 coups|year = 2006|isbn = 2-89540-194-2|page=126}}</ref>
The Cinémathèque complex was extensively redesigned from 1994 to 1997 by the architectural firm of [[Saucier + Perrotte]].<ref name="CE">{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/saucier-perrotte-architectes/|title=Saucier + Perrotte Architects|last=Livesay|first=Graham|work=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=2009-04-10}}</ref> Awards for the design included the 1999 Governor General's Award for Architecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archrecord.construction.com/projects/bts/archives/perform/2000/0011Cinematheque.asp|title=Cinémathèque Québécoise |work=Architectural Record|publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies|accessdate=2009-04-10}}</ref>
In 2017 the Cinémathèque québécoise collaborated with the Vancouver Cinematheque, the Toronto International Film Festival and Library and Archives Canada mounted a retrospective of 150 culturally significant films.<ref>[https://www.vancourier.com/community/fred-unleeshed-jan-11-2018-1.7032000 "Fred UnLEEshed"]. Fred Lee / ''Vancouver Courier'', January 11, 2017</ref>
